All right.

*A breath.*

There was a class. In seminary. My first year. A man named Professor Ellington — small, bald, terrible coffee breath, the kindest face I have ever seen on a human being. He was teaching Romans. And he stopped one afternoon in the middle of a sentence and he looked at us — there were eleven of us in the room — and he said, *gentlemen, before we go any further, I need each of you to tell me, out loud, what you would do if you discovered tomorrow that none of this was true.*

*A pause.*

I left that night. I packed a duffel bag and I drove home to my mother's house in Minnesota. I told everyone I had a crisis of vocation. *A small, terrible breath.* That was not the question I could not answer. The question I could not answer was *what would you do if you discovered tomorrow that all of it was true.*

*He looks at his open hands.*

Because I knew, friend. I knew what the answer was. The answer was *everything would have to change.* Everything. The house. The car. The career. The — *he stops* — the comfortable Lutheran life of a Lutheran boy from a Lutheran town. And I was not — *a breath* — I was not prepared to find out it was true. So I left before he could prove it to me.

*A long pause.*

I came back to the faith ten years later. I came back because I could not honestly walk away from the texts. But I came back — *and this is the thing, friend, this is the thing I have never said* — I came back on terms. ~I came back as a man who would teach it and not live it. Who would carry it and not be carried by it. Who would put it on sixteen-year-olds and not put it on himself.~

*His voice is almost gone.*

